The AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) system can prove to be very useful in an e-commerce organization to safeguard the sensitive customer and business data. It can ensure that employees can only access the information that is necessary for their job function, thereby reducing the risk of a data breach. 

For instance, consider the scenario where an e-commerce site has different teams such as the Shipping team, Customer Service team, and the Payment Processing team. 

Using AWS IAM, you can create separate roles for each of these teams. For the Shipping team, you can create a policy that only allows them to view and update the customer shipping information. They won't be allowed to view the customer's payment details or any other details that are irrelevant to their job function. 

```
{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": [
                "dynamodb:GetItem",
                "dynamodb:UpdateItem"
            ],
            "Resource": "arn:aws:dynamodb:us-east-1:123456789012:table/ShippingInfo"
        }
    ]
}
```

Likewise, the Customer Service team can only access the customer's contact information, not their payment details or shipping information. Similarly, while the Payment Processing team can access the customer's payment details, they cannot view their contact or shipping information. This ensures the principle of least privilege is upheld, with each team being able to only access and perform actions on the resources necessary for their roles.
